		<article class="item-blog col-md-4 post-4111 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-events" id="post-4111">	

        	<div class="post-container">

			



<div class="post-name">

	<h2 class="entry-title">

		<a href="http://alcuinsociety.com/erik-kwakkel-lecture-reading-an-invisible-book/" title="Erik Kwakkel Lecture: Reading an invisible book"> Erik Kwakkel Lecture: Reading an invisible book</a>

	</h2>

    <div class="entry-meta entry-header">
	<span class="published">January 12, 2019 by Gina Page</span>
	<span class="meta-sep"> / </span>
	<span class="comment-count"><span>Comments Off<span class="screen-reader-text"> on Erik Kwakkel Lecture: Reading an invisible book</span></span></span>
    
    </div>
</div>



<div class="entry-content">

    <p>Erik Kwakkel, Professor, UBC iSchool (Library, Archival and Information Studies), will present a talk <strong>Reading an invisible book: Using x-ray to reconstruct destroyed medieval manuscripts.</strong></p>
<div>Date:  <span id="OBJ_PREFIX_DWT19_com_zimbra_date" class="Object" role="link">Thursday, March 7</span>, 2019</div>
<div>Time:  7 pm</div>
<div>Location: The Post at 750 Hamilton Street in the Startup Studio</div>
<div>Please register on <a href="https://www.eventbrite.ca/e/erik-kwakkel-reading-an-invisible-book-tickets-54809359269?aff=eac2">Eventbrite</a>.</div>
<div><img class="size-medium wp-image-4152 alignleft" src="http://alcuinsociety.com/content/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2019_invisible_book_rose-300x232.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="232" srcset="http://alcuinsociety.com/content/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2019_invisible_book_rose-300x232.jpg 300w, http://alcuinsociety.com/content/wp-content/uploads/2019/01/2019_invisible_book_rose-1024x791.jpg 1024w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></div>
<div>
<p>This lecture focuses on a period in history in which books were systematically destroyed. At the close of the Middle Ages, <em>c</em>. 1450-1500, when the freshly invented printed book had become the new norm, old-fashioned handwritten manuscripts of the medieval period were destroyed by the thousands. Many of these manuscripts were upcycled by bookbinders in the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, who used their firm parchment pages to reinforce the inside of bookbindings. As a result, thousands of manuscripts, reduced to small strips, remain invisibly embedded inside surviving bookbindings. Unless a binding is damaged, it is only with special x-ray techniques that these medieval ‘stowaways’ can be made visible. This lecture discusses the systematic destruction of books at the close of the medieval period and the innovative ways in which they are studied today.</p>
<p><strong>Erik Kwakkel</strong> is Professor at the iSchool (Library, Archival and Information Studies), The University of British Columbia, where he teaches the History of the Book. His research interests are related to the script and material design of medieval manuscripts. He has published several monographs and edited volumes devoted to the culture of the medieval book, including, most recently, <em>The European Book in the Twelfth Century</em> (Cambridge University Press, 2018, co-edited with Rodney Thomson) and <em>Books Before Print</em> (Arc Humanities Press, 2018), a textbook for undergraduate teaching. He is co-author (with Francis Newton) of <em>Medicine at Monte Cassino: Constantine the African and the Oldest Manuscript of his Pantegni</em> (forthcoming with Brepols in 2019). In 2015 Kwakkel was appointed to the <em>Comité International de Paléographie Latine</em> (CIPL).</p>
</div>

</div>







            </div>

		</article>

                

		
                

		
                

        
                

